{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649672"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:06:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:06:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18371"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18371"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.55,0,0.05,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11089"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74577"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11089"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18371"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60069"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7237"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25714"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25715"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25839"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74577"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe tibial nerve provides innervation to several muscles in the lower limb.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscles is supplied by the tibial nerve?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Peroneus longus","Gastrocnemius","Sartorius","Extensor digitorum longus","Tibialis anterior"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe tibial nerve is responsible for innervating the muscles in the posterior compartment of the leg, which are primarily involved in plantarflexion and toe flexion. The \u003Cstrong\u003Egastrocnemius\u003C/strong\u003E muscle, located in the posterior compartment, is one of the primary muscles responsible for plantarflexion of the foot at the ankle joint. This muscle is innervated by the tibial nerve. Other muscles include the soleus, plantaris, popliteus, tibialis posterior, flexor digitorum longus and flexor hallucis longus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETibialis anterior\u003C/strong\u003E is located in the anterior compartment of the leg and is innervated by the deep fibular (peroneal) nerve. It is responsible for dorsiflexion of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeroneus longus\u003C/strong\u003E is located in the lateral compartment of the leg and is innervated by the superficial fibular (peroneal) nerve. It is involved in eversion of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtensor digitorum longus\u003C/strong\u003E is also located in the anterior compartment and is innervated by the deep fibular (peroneal) nerve. It extends the toes and dorsiflexes the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESartorius\u003C/strong\u003E is located in the anterior compartment of the thigh and is innervated by the femoral nerve. It is involved in flexion, abduction, and lateral rotation of the hip, as well as flexion of the knee.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The tibial nerve innervates the posterior compartment of the leg, including muscles responsible for plantarflexion and toe flexion.","Understanding the innervation of leg muscles is crucial for diagnosing nerve injuries and planning surgical interventions."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60069"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18371"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60069"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T08:16:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T08:17:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11089"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74577"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrie